From: knsol <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH] debug: instrument write_to_storage with 1-in-100 LOG_INF

Patch 0032 was supposed to unblock SD writes during BLE connections by
removing the unconditional storage_is_on=true on connect. But after
flashing, file_num_array[0] is still 0 forever and serial shows ~1
cmd24 every 8 seconds (vs the ~5 cmd24/sec we expected from the codec
output rate).

This patch adds a once-per-100-calls LOG_INF at the top of
write_to_storage() so we can confirm in serial whether the function is
reaching the disk path at all. If it logs at the expected rate, the
gate is fine and the issue is downstream (write_to_file / FATFS). If
it doesn't log, something upstream (pusher gating, ring buffer, mutex)
is still blocking.

Logging frequency 1/100 keeps CDC ringbuf safe at codec rate (~100 fps
→ 1 log per second).
---
diff --git a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
--- a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
+++ b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
@@ -657,6 +657,15 @@ static uint16_t buffer_offset = 0;
 // out to both SD and BLE.
 bool write_to_storage(void)
 { // max possible packing
+    /* Patch 0033: instrumentation. Logs every 100th call so serial
+     * shows write activity without spamming. Helps confirm whether SD
+     * writes reach this layer at all (vs being gated upstream). */
+    static uint32_t wts_count = 0;
+    if ((wts_count % 100) == 0) {
+        LOG_INF("write_to_storage: count=%u  buf_off=%u", wts_count, buffer_offset);
+    }
+    wts_count++;
+
     uint8_t *buffer = tx_buffer + 2;
     uint8_t packet_size = (uint8_t) (tx_buffer_size + OPUS_PREFIX_LENGTH);

